snippet.description:
Rap mogul to perform alongside The Game, stand together as a voice for the marijuana industry

San Bernardino, CA ‚Äî April 21, 2017 ‚Äî High Times, the voice of the cannabis movement since 1974, revealed a last minute surprise for SoCal Cannabis Cup ticket holders today that multi-platinum, grammy award winning rapper, actor, and businessman Curtis ‚Äú50 Cent‚Äù Jackson will be performing Saturday night.

The rap mogul will be joining the already jam packed lineup ‚Äî which the LAist has said rivals the second weekend of Coachella ‚Äî featuring Nas, Damian Marley, Wu-Tang Clan, Lit, A$AP Ferg, Vic Mensa, Method Man & Redman, Chief Keef, and The Game. And despite the public animosity between 50 Cent and The Game, the two are expected to perform together at the festival.

The Cannabis Cup, which was established in 1988 as an industry trade show, has grown into a booming events business spanning multiple states around the country. In recent years the industry has catapulted, and in turn, the festival has grown to include seminars, cooking competitions, and a topical massage spa, in addition to the musical performances and demonstrations from top companies. snippet.title: Joe Budden EXPOSES DJ Akademiks Is An Awkward DWEEB, Talks Drake, Kendrick Lamar's Humble, Big Sean
snippet.description:
Joe Budden live on Periscope today with DJ Akademiks

Joe Budden SONS DJ Akademiks & EXPOSES How Big Of A Geek Dweeb He Is On Set Of Their New Complex Show

Complex today announced the series premiere of ‚ÄúEVERYDAY STRUGGLE,‚Äù a new daily morning show covering the biggest news and hot-button issues facing hip-hop music and pop-culture. Serving as co-hosts, famed rapper and host of ‚ÄúI‚Äôll Name This Podcast Later‚Äù Joe Budden and opinionated urban media commentator DJ Akademiks will face-off each day about the artist they feel deserve their top spots, who‚Äôs fallen off, wage their bets on brewing rap beef, analyze the latest social media buzz and determine which artists are moving the culture forward.

Each heated discussion will be filmed in-studio and moderated by Complex News‚Äô Noah Callahan-Bever and Nadeska Alexis. Conversations will get intense and opinions are taken to the next level as Joe and Akademiks battle it out every morning at 11:00 AM on YouTube.com/Complexnews starting on April 10. 
 
"While I would love to say something really heartwarming and politically correct, I'm not sure that would properly convey the sentiment I think all of us have. So from Myself, Akademics & the good ppl over at Complex... we bout to F*** S*** UP, ‚Äú remarked Joe Budden. 
 
"They always say it's not about who did it first it's who did it best... but after seeing the vision for the show and the great people around it, I truly believe we can kill two birds with one stone. Joe and I along with complex will definitely be delivering some epic moments and setting the canvas for very interesting and insightful dialogue, " commented DJ Akademiks.
 
Joe Budden has been making waves in the music industry as a solo artist and member of the hip-hop supergroup Slaughterhouse. Budden achieved commercial success as a solo artist with the 2003 single ‚ÄúPump It Up.‚Äù Throughout his career, Budden has released seven studio albums, numerous mixtapes and had singles featured in soundtracks for several blockbuster films and video games. In 2014 Budden joined New York‚Äôs Hot 97‚Äôs morning crew as co-host where he was known to have ‚Äúno filter‚Äù on many of hip-hop‚Äôs controversial topics. Budden went on expand his media industry presence on television, spending two seasons on VH1‚Äôs popular ‚ÄúLove and Hip-Hop‚Äù series and season six of ‚ÄúCouples Therapy.‚Äù
 
DJ Akademiks launched his career in the music industry as a disc jockey, spinning at local parties and creating beats as a college student studying biomathematics at Rutgers University. During that time, Akademiks launched his first YouTube page as a way to promote his projects but expanded his channel to include on-campus interviews with students on various hip-hop topics. Known as the ‚Äúone-man hip-hop TMZ,‚Äù DJ Akademiks has amassed a following of over 1Million subscribers on his YouTube channel where he serves a the millennial generation‚Äôs go-to source for hip-hop news and culture, often weaving satire into controversial reports on hip-hop music news and current events within the entertainment industry.

snippet.title: Naturi Naughton victim impact statement on being hacked
snippet.description:
In a victim impact statement, Naturi Naughton, a lead actor in the TV show ‚ÄúPower,‚Äù said she felt violated when her emails were stolen by Alonzo Knowles, who was sentenced on Tuesday. By UNITED STATES ATTORNEY‚ÄôS OFFICE FOR THE SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK

A Bahamian man who hacked into the email accounts of celebrities and athletes and later wrote in a jailhouse email that after his release he would ‚Äúshake up hollywood for real!‚Äù was sentenced to five years in prison on Tuesday.

The sentence was roughly double the number of years suggested under federal sentencing guidelines.

The man, Alonzo Knowles, 24, had used his illicit access to the celebrity accounts to obtain unreleased movie and television scripts and personal information, which he then tried to sell for thousands of dollars, prosecutors said. Mr. Knowles had also stolen unreleased music, financial documents, and nude and intimate images and videos, the government said.

Kristy J. Greenberg, a prosecutor, said in Federal District Court in Manhattan that Mr. Knowles‚Äôs motivation had been greed. ‚ÄúHe had a singular focus on becoming rich and famous,‚Äù she said, ‚Äúby disseminating personal information of celebrities and exploiting them.‚Äù

Several victims had submitted statements to the judge. Naturi Naughton, an actress in the Starz drama ‚ÄúPower,‚Äù said in a video statement that Mr. Knowles had hacked her personal emails and stolen six scripts of the show, and then ‚Äútried to extort me, the producer, 50 Cent and my showrunner.‚Äù

‚ÄúI have never felt more violated and out of control in my entire life,‚Äù Ms. Naughton said.

Judge Paul A. Engelmayer of Federal District Court called Mr. Knowles‚Äôs crimes ‚Äúdeeply troubling,‚Äù and told him that he had chosen to use ‚Äúyour gifts, your know-how, for dark and lawless ends.‚Äù

When Mr. Knowles pleaded guilty in federal court in May, he apologized, saying he knew what he had done was wrong. But he then wrote in emails sent from jail that he planned to write a book and reveal the secrets of the victims whose accounts he had broken into, the government said.

‚ÄúIm name dropping everyone involved and what I know,‚Äù Mr. Knowles wrote, ‚Äúand im including pictures of paperwork that aint public.‚Äù

He wrote that he would charge $35 a copy, would hack into Twitter accounts to promote his book and that his goal was to make money. ‚ÄúEveryone loves gossip,‚Äù he wrote. ‚ÄúI cant wait to get out i already know how the cover is gonna look.‚Äù

The emails, which prosecutors cited in a sentencing memorandum to Judge Engelmayer, had been sent on a Bureau of Prisons email system that prisoners may use after they give consent to the monitoring of their messages.

The judge said that Mr. Knowles‚Äôs jailhouse messages were ‚Äúdevoid of any remorse,‚Äù and showed that if he were released from prison any time soon, he ‚Äúwould be a clear and present danger to commit the very same crime again.‚Äù

‚ÄúUnavoidably, Mr. Knowles,‚Äù Judge Engelmayer said, ‚Äúthe public has a significant interest in your being behind bars in federal prison where you have no access to the internet and no practical ability to do such harm.‚Äù

Mr. Knowles, who had pleaded guilty to charges of identity theft and criminal copyright infringement, read a brief statement, apologizing to the court and his victims. ‚ÄúWhat I did was wrong,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúI could have ruined people‚Äôs lives.‚Äù

His lawyer, Clay Kaminsky, had asked for a sentence of 14 months. Mr. Knowles had faced a maximum sentence of 10 years; the federal sentencing guidelines, which are not binding on a judge, had suggested 27 to 33 months, his plea agreement shows.

Mr. Knowles was arrested last December after he flew to New York to meet with a man who was posing as a potential buyer of the scripts he had stolen. The man was actually an undercover agent.

The case drew attention in part because it followed the widely publicized hacking of Sony Pictures Entertainment in 2014. The Knowles case also showed how a hacker could obtain confidential information from victims by targeting the accounts of their friends and associates, a process Mr. Knowles called ‚Äúsocial engineering.‚Äù

‚ÄúIn the wee hours of the night, when his victims were likely asleep, Knowles trolled his victims‚Äô private email accounts, obtaining their most personal communications,‚Äù the office of Preet Bharara, the United States attorney for the Southern District of New York, had said in its sentencing memorandum.
